="Once upon a time, there were also an insane amount of deaths due to malnourishment. I recommend people to look up Integrated Pest Management. I love organic, but in specific cases, using chemicals can have less of an environmental impact than an organic management method. As an example, growing wine, one uses the same plants for multiple years. Some pests/pathogens have no effective organic pesticide, but people often uses stuff like sulfur, and LOTS of it, which in the end has more of a detrimental effect on the soil than a single application of a pesticide meant for that specific type of pest. One could ignore taking any action at all, but as a farmer, you would lose your entire source of income, as well as having to buy new plant materials. This costs lots of money and the environmental impact of shipping new plants, disturbing the soil by digging up all the old dead plants and all of the sulfur in the ground from prior organic methods ends up as an environmental net loss. IPM concentrates on mechanical and biological management but doesn't exclude scenarios like these. Farmers have to follow the step-by-step strategy for IPM to be a working concept though, doing things haphazardly helps no-one."
